  "prompt": "How has legislation evolved to combat money laundering?",
  "response": "The evolution of anti-money laundering (AML) legislation has been a complex and ongoing process:\n\n1. Early Developments\n- Bank Secrecy Act (1970) in the United States\n- First international recognition of money laundering as a criminal issue\n- Initial focus on reporting large cash transactions\n\n2. 1980s Advancements\n- Increased awareness of money laundering's connection to drug trafficking\n- United Nations Convention against Illicit Traffic in Narcotic Drugs (1988)\n- Enhanced international cooperation\n\n3. 1990s Significant Reforms\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) established\n- First comprehensive international AML standards\n- Expanded regulatory requirements for financial institutions\n- Criminalization of money laundering in multiple jurisdictions\n\n4. Post-9/11 Legislation\n- USA PATRIOT Act (2001)\n- Stronger emphasis on combating terrorist financing\n- Enhanced due diligence requirements\n- Increased information sharing between agencies\n\n5. Recent Developments\n- More stringent Know Your Customer (KYC) regulations\n- Cryptocurrency and digital asset regulations\n- Increased focus on beneficial ownership transparency\n- Enhanced international information exchange mechanisms\n\nThese legislative changes reflect growing complexity and sophistication in financial crime prevention.",
